1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,625
CueDeck's display system has eleven content modes.

2
00:00:07,925 --> 00:00:10,925
Each one is designed for a specific screen,

3
00:00:11,225 --> 00:00:14,975
a specific moment, or a specific audience in your venue.

4
00:00:15,275 --> 00:00:19,025
In this episode we're going through all of them —

5
00:00:19,325 --> 00:00:21,950
what they look like, what they're for,

6
00:00:22,250 --> 00:00:24,250
and when to use them.

7
00:00:24,550 --> 00:00:28,300
I'll go deep on the four most commonly used modes

8
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:30,850
and move quicker through the rest.

9
00:00:31,150 --> 00:00:33,150
Let's go.

10
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:35,700
The eleven modes are: Schedule, Agenda,

11
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,250
Sponsor, Countdown, Clock, Next Up, Ticker,

12
00:00:38,550 --> 00:00:40,800
Recall, Timeline, Programme, and Stage Timer.

13
00:00:41,100 --> 00:00:44,850
Each one pulls live data from Supabase in real time.

14
00:00:45,150 --> 00:00:47,775
There's no refresh button, no manual updates.

15
00:00:48,075 --> 00:00:51,075
When a session goes LIVE in the console,

16
00:00:51,375 --> 00:00:55,875
every display showing schedule or agenda data updates automatically within a second.

17
00:00:56,175 --> 00:00:58,425
Let me walk through each one.

18
00:00:58,725 --> 00:01:00,725
Schedule is the workhorse mode.

19
00:01:01,025 --> 00:01:04,775
It shows the full programme list for today's event —

20
00:01:05,075 --> 00:01:08,450
all sessions in chronological order, with the session title,

21
00:01:08,750 --> 00:01:11,375
speaker, room, planned time, and current status.

22
00:01:11,675 --> 00:01:16,175
Sessions that are LIVE or in OVERRUN get a pulsing green badge.

23
00:01:16,475 --> 00:01:20,975
Sessions that are READY or CALLING get an amber 'coming up' indicator.

24
00:01:21,275 --> 00:01:23,275
Ended sessions are dimmed.

25
00:01:23,575 --> 00:01:25,575
Cancelled sessions disappear.

26
00:01:25,875 --> 00:01:29,250
If you've applied a delay in the production console,

27
00:01:29,550 --> 00:01:32,925
the scheduled times shown here update to reflect that.

28
00:01:33,225 --> 00:01:36,975
So your lobby screens are always showing the current working

29
00:01:37,275 --> 00:01:40,275
programme, not the original one from last week.

30
00:01:40,575 --> 00:01:43,200
Best used for: main lobby entrance displays,

31
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:47,250
registration area, any screen where attendees need to know the

32
00:01:47,550 --> 00:01:49,800
full day's programme at a glance.

33
00:01:50,100 --> 00:01:53,850
In the display modal, you can add a Room filter

34
00:01:54,150 --> 00:01:57,900
— that limits this display to only showing sessions from

35
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:03,075
one specific room, which is great for corridor screens outside a particular hall.

36
00:02:03,375 --> 00:02:05,625
Agenda is the room grid view.

37
00:02:05,925 --> 00:02:08,175
Instead of a single chronological list,

38
00:02:08,475 --> 00:02:11,850
it shows multiple columns — one per room —

39
00:02:12,150 --> 00:02:15,525
each with that room's sessions stacked in time order.

40
00:02:15,825 --> 00:02:20,325
This is your 'at-a-glance what's happening in all rooms right now' mode.

41
00:02:20,625 --> 00:02:24,375
Up to four columns fit comfortably on a landscape screen.

42
00:02:24,675 --> 00:02:27,300
LIVE sessions get a bold green card.

43
00:02:27,600 --> 00:02:29,850
READY sessions get a ready indicator.

44
00:02:30,150 --> 00:02:33,900
Best used for: foyer screens at the entrance to a

45
00:02:34,200 --> 00:02:37,950
multi-track conference, where attendees are choosing which session to attend.

46
00:02:38,250 --> 00:02:42,000
It lets them compare tracks in one look rather than

47
00:02:42,300 --> 00:02:44,300
scanning a linear list.

48
00:02:44,600 --> 00:02:46,850
Timeline is similar to Schedule but

49
00:02:47,150 --> 00:02:50,900
with a cleaner two-column layout: a left column showing the

50
00:02:51,200 --> 00:02:54,950
start time, and a right column with the session title,

51
00:02:55,250 --> 00:02:57,250
speaker, room and duration.

52
00:02:57,550 --> 00:03:00,175
There's no room filter grid here —

53
00:03:00,475 --> 00:03:03,850
it's all sessions in one stream, sorted by time.

54
00:03:04,150 --> 00:03:08,275
The real difference from Schedule is the scroll and paginate behaviour.

55
00:03:08,575 --> 00:03:11,200
Timeline mode supports both smooth auto-scroll and

56
00:03:11,500 --> 00:03:14,875
page-by-page pagination, which you configure in the display settings.

57
00:03:15,175 --> 00:03:18,925
This makes it ideal for a tall portrait screen —

58
00:03:19,225 --> 00:03:23,350
a vertical monitor mounted in a column or on a stand.

59
00:03:23,650 --> 00:03:26,275
Best used for: tall format lobby displays,

60
00:03:26,575 --> 00:03:28,825
tablet stands, or portrait orientation kiosks.

61
00:03:29,125 --> 00:03:31,375
Programme is the most information-dense mode.

62
00:03:31,675 --> 00:03:34,675
It's a matrix: time on the vertical axis,

63
00:03:34,975 --> 00:03:36,975
rooms across the horizontal.

64
00:03:37,275 --> 00:03:39,525
Each cell is a session block,

65
00:03:39,825 --> 00:03:42,075
sized to reflect its actual duration.

66
00:03:42,375 --> 00:03:46,125
Think of it as a visual conference schedule grid —

67
00:03:46,425 --> 00:03:49,800
the kind you'd see printed in a conference booklet,

68
00:03:50,100 --> 00:03:52,100
but live and updating.

69
00:03:52,400 --> 00:03:55,025
Best used for: large lobby screens where

70
00:03:55,325 --> 00:03:57,950
attendees have time to study the grid,

71
00:03:58,250 --> 00:04:03,125
or a director's secondary monitor for a quick structural overview of the day.

72
00:04:03,425 --> 00:04:06,050
It works best with landscape orientation and

73
00:04:06,350 --> 00:04:08,350
at least a 1080p display.

74
00:04:08,650 --> 00:04:10,900
Next Up is a two-panel display:

75
00:04:11,200 --> 00:04:14,950
the current LIVE or READY session fills the top two-thirds

76
00:04:15,250 --> 00:04:19,000
of the screen in large type — title, speaker, room.

77
00:04:19,300 --> 00:04:22,675
The bottom third shows the next session coming up.

78
00:04:22,975 --> 00:04:24,975
This is a production-oriented mode.

79
00:04:25,275 --> 00:04:29,025
It's for the screen at the back of the main

80
00:04:29,325 --> 00:04:33,075
hall that the director glances at to confirm what's live,

81
00:04:33,375 --> 00:04:37,125
or for a confidence monitor at the stage entrance so

82
00:04:37,425 --> 00:04:40,050
the next speaker knows they're coming up.

83
00:04:40,350 --> 00:04:43,350
The live session shows a pulsing LIVE badge.

84
00:04:43,650 --> 00:04:47,400
When the session ends and the next one becomes live,

85
00:04:47,700 --> 00:04:51,075
the display transitions automatically — no manual action needed.

86
00:04:51,375 --> 00:04:55,125
Countdown shows a single large timer counting down to the

87
00:04:55,425 --> 00:04:57,675
start of the next session, or

88
00:04:57,975 --> 00:05:02,100
to the start of the event if nothing has begun yet.

89
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:06,150
Best used for: pre-event lobby screens building anticipation before the

90
00:05:06,450 --> 00:05:10,200
opening keynote, or a break screen showing how many minutes

91
00:05:10,500 --> 00:05:14,625
are left in the coffee break before the next session begins.

92
00:05:14,925 --> 00:05:17,550
Clock is exactly what it sounds like:

93
00:05:17,850 --> 00:05:21,600
a full-screen clock showing the current time in large format.

94
00:05:21,900 --> 00:05:24,150
CueDeck uses its server-synced clock —

95
00:05:24,450 --> 00:05:28,200
the same `correctedNow()` function that drives all timing in the

96
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:32,250
production console — so the clock on your display is

97
00:05:32,550 --> 00:05:35,925
accurate to within a few milliseconds of the server.

98
00:05:36,225 --> 00:05:39,975
Best used for: registration areas, the back of the room

99
00:05:40,275 --> 00:05:44,025
for the director's reference, or anywhere a precise time display

100
00:05:44,325 --> 00:05:46,575
is more useful than programme information.

101
00:05:46,875 --> 00:05:49,875
Sponsor mode cycles through your sponsor logos —

102
00:05:50,175 --> 00:05:53,925
images you upload to CueDeck's asset store in the Sponsors

103
00:05:54,225 --> 00:05:56,225
section of the signage panel.

104
00:05:56,525 --> 00:06:00,275
Each logo appears full-screen or in a grid depending on

105
00:06:00,575 --> 00:06:02,825
how many sponsors you've uploaded, and

106
00:06:03,125 --> 00:06:05,375
the display rotates through them automatically.

107
00:06:05,675 --> 00:06:08,675
Sponsorship is a revenue stream at most events,

108
00:06:08,975 --> 00:06:11,975
and sponsors expect their logo to be visible.

109
00:06:12,275 --> 00:06:16,025
Sponsor mode lets you run a professional-looking sponsor reel on

110
00:06:16,325 --> 00:06:19,700
any display without any video editing or external software.

111
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,375
Best used for: break screens, lobby displays during registration,

112
00:06:23,675 --> 00:06:25,675
corridor monitors between sessions.

113
00:06:25,975 --> 00:06:28,600
Ticker shows a scrolling text message —

114
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:30,900
like a news ticker.

115
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:35,325
The message comes from the Broadcast bar in the production console.

116
00:06:35,625 --> 00:06:37,875
When the director sends a broadcast,

117
00:06:38,175 --> 00:06:41,550
displays in ticker mode scroll it across the screen.

118
00:06:41,850 --> 00:06:44,100
Best used for: supplementary information screens,

119
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:48,150
announcements during sessions — things like 'Lunch is now being

120
00:06:48,450 --> 00:06:50,700
served in the Atrium' — where

121
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:55,125
you want a non-intrusive rolling message rather than a full-screen alert.

122
00:06:55,425 --> 00:06:58,800
Recall is a dedicated speaker and attendee recall mode.

123
00:06:59,100 --> 00:07:02,850
It shows a large-format 'PLEASE RETURN TO YOUR SEATS' or

124
00:07:03,150 --> 00:07:05,775
speaker recall message, with a countdown timer.

125
00:07:06,075 --> 00:07:09,825
The signage operator can trigger this globally from the context

126
00:07:10,125 --> 00:07:12,375
panel with a single button —

127
00:07:12,675 --> 00:07:14,925
it overrides all displays simultaneously and

128
00:07:15,225 --> 00:07:17,225
shows the recall screen.

129
00:07:17,525 --> 00:07:22,025
When the recall is cleared, displays snap back to their configured modes.

130
00:07:22,325 --> 00:07:25,325
Best used for: end-of-break recall, between sessions when

131
00:07:25,625 --> 00:07:27,625
you need people moving quickly.

132
00:07:27,925 --> 00:07:30,550
Stage Timer is the newest mode and

133
00:07:30,850 --> 00:07:34,225
probably the most important one for your on-stage team.

134
00:07:34,525 --> 00:07:38,275
It turns a display into a speaker-facing countdown timer —

135
00:07:38,575 --> 00:07:41,950
the clock the presenter looks at while they're talking.

136
00:07:42,250 --> 00:07:44,500
You get a huge colour-coded countdown:

137
00:07:44,800 --> 00:07:47,050
green when there's plenty of time,

138
00:07:47,350 --> 00:07:51,100
amber when under five minutes, red when under two minutes.

139
00:07:51,400 --> 00:07:54,400
OVERRUN switches to a flashing red plus-MM:SS counter.

140
00:07:54,700 --> 00:07:58,450
HOLD freezes the timer in orange with a PAUSED indicator.

141
00:07:58,750 --> 00:08:01,000
And when nothing is live yet,

142
00:08:01,300 --> 00:08:03,925
it shows a 'NEXT UP IN' countdown.

143
00:08:04,225 --> 00:08:07,225
This mode gets its own full episode —

144
00:08:07,525 --> 00:08:11,650
episode ten — where we'll walk through every state in detail.

145
00:08:11,950 --> 00:08:14,575
But the quick summary is: one display,

146
00:08:14,875 --> 00:08:17,500
one URL, the speaker is always informed.

147
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:21,175
Before we close out, one more thing: global overrides.

148
00:08:21,475 --> 00:08:25,225
These appear in the context panel for the director and

149
00:08:25,525 --> 00:08:29,275
signage role, and they let you switch all displays simultaneously

150
00:08:29,575 --> 00:08:31,575
with a single click.

151
00:08:31,875 --> 00:08:35,250
Break Screen puts everything into a neutral break mode.

152
00:08:35,550 --> 00:08:38,925
Five-Minute Recall triggers the recall screen across all displays.

153
00:08:39,225 --> 00:08:42,225
Sponsor Reel pushes every display into sponsor rotation.

154
00:08:42,525 --> 00:08:45,150
Back to Schedule clears the override and

155
00:08:45,450 --> 00:08:48,075
restores each display to its configured mode.

156
00:08:48,375 --> 00:08:51,000
These overrides bypass individual display settings temporarily.

157
00:08:51,300 --> 00:08:55,050
When you clear them, every display goes back to whatever

158
00:08:55,350 --> 00:08:57,600
mode you originally configured for it.

159
00:08:57,900 --> 00:09:01,650
It's the fastest way to manage a whole venue when

160
00:09:01,950 --> 00:09:03,950
you need instant control.

161
00:09:04,250 --> 00:09:06,875
Eleven modes, each with a specific job.

162
00:09:07,175 --> 00:09:10,925
The ones you'll use most are probably Schedule for the

163
00:09:11,225 --> 00:09:13,850
lobby, Next Up for the stage entrance,

164
00:09:14,150 --> 00:09:16,400
Stage Timer for the speaker-facing monitor,

165
00:09:16,700 --> 00:09:18,950
and Sponsor for breaks — but

166
00:09:19,250 --> 00:09:21,875
they're all there when you need them.

167
00:09:22,175 --> 00:09:24,800
Set a display to sequence mode and

168
00:09:25,100 --> 00:09:28,100
it can rotate through several of these automatically,

169
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:33,275
giving you a professional multi-format display without any manual intervention throughout the day.

170
00:09:33,575 --> 00:09:35,825
Next episode: the Stage Confidence Monitor.

171
00:09:36,125 --> 00:09:39,875
That's the fullscreen overlay on the director's own screen —

172
00:09:40,175 --> 00:09:44,675
a different tool from signage, purpose-built for the person running the show.

173
00:09:44,975 --> 00:09:46,975
See you there.
